<h1>Hello, Rails!</h1>
<ul>
  <% @articles.each do |article| %>
    <li>
      <%= article.title %>
    </li>
    <li>
      body: <%= article.body %>
    </li>
  <% end %>
</ul>

<ul>
  <% @articles.each do |article| %>
    <li>
      <a href="/articles/<%= article.id %>">
        <%= article.title %>
      </a>
    </li>
  <% end %>
</ul>

<h1>Link_to helper</h1>

 <%# The link_to helper renders a link with its first argument as the link's text 
 and its second argument as the link's destination. If we pass a model object 
 as the second argument, link_to will call the appropriate path helper to convert 
 the object to a path. For example, if we pass an article, link_to will call 
 article_path The link_to helper renders a link with its first argument as the 
 link's text and its second argument as the link's destination. If we pass a model 
 object as the second argument, link_to will call the appropriate path helper 
 to convert the object to a path. For example, if we pass an article, 
 link_to will call article_path %>

<ul>
  <% @articles.each do |article| %>
    <li>
      <%= link_to article.title, article %>
    </li>
  <% end %>
</ul>
<% link_to "New Article", new_article_path%>